{I like a lot this psychlogical example which, hopefully, will help the
readers discover theirs and thus eliminate such episodes, if possible!} 1. e4
e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Bxf6 gxf6 7. Nf3 f5 8. Nc3 a6
9. Qe2 b5 10. O-O-O b4 11. Na4 Qd5 12. Kb1 Nd7 13. c4 Qe4+ 14. Qxe4 fxe4 15.
Nd2 Bb7 16. Kc2 Bc6 17. Kb3 Rd8 18. Be2 Rg8 19. Rhg1 Rg5 20. c5 e5 21. f3 e3
22. Ne4 Bxe4 23. fxe4 exd4 24. Bxa6 Rxc5 25. Nxc5 Nxc5+ {Without false modesty,
I absolutely loved the way I played so far. I was sharp, calculating and
seeing many lines, the opening phase went great, in other words: Black
outplayed White and now it's purely about collecting the dividents.} 26. Kc4 $1
{The exclamation mark stands for the surprise it gave me during the game. My
eyes popped and I started doubting myself. Simply because I didn't consider
this move doesn't mean it is a brilliant one, so I should just sit back, relax
and look at the board again. Instead, I panicked.} Nxa6 {Nothing wrong yet but
I can say that mentally I was disturbed: how can I ruin such a beautifully
constructed game by not seeing one move? Needless to say how poisonous those
thoughts are.} ({Black is so winning that it doesn't really matter which move
will be played.} 26... d3 {rolling the pawns}) ({Or} 26... c6 {Zugzwang?!:)}
27. Rxd4 Ra8 $19) 27. Rxd4 Rxd4+ {Following the down trend triggered earlier
by not seeing one of my opponent's moves. Exchanging rooks is a very bad idea
in those type of endgames, with two pieces against a rook.} ({Keeping the rook
is essential for stopping White's defensive ideas and for attacking plans as
well.} 27... Ra8 $19) 28. Kxd4 b3 {More panick as now the clock is ticking too.
In my defense though, here I started calculating again and it looked to me
like the best move. And it is:)} 29. a4 {After being so winning before, now
Black must keep an eye on that a-pawn.} Nb4 (29... Bb4 $142 30. Kd3 Bd2 $19 {
followed by the advance of the c-pawn.}) 30. Kc3 Bc5 31. Rd1 ({During the game
I thought} 31. Kxb3 Nd3 32. Kc4 e2 {should be winning but now I am not so sure.
..} 33. Rh1 Bf2 34. Kxd3 e1=Q 35. Rxe1 Bxe1 {White has very good chances to
hold, if it is not a draw already. The readers can let us know in the comments.
}) 31... Nc6 32. Kd3 Bb6 33. Rc1 Kd7 34. Rc3 Nd4 {White's flag went down to 0.
00 but the position is again winning for Black. Hope to remember next time
this typical occurence: a surprising move which one missed shouldn't
destabilize the mind nor the position.} 0-1

