{This is an illustrative example of how important endgame knowledge and
technique are for saving energy.} 37. Rc7+ ({It is quite funny to see the
troubles that engines have in these positions. They don't realize that} 37. e4
{is technically winning since the e and f pawns are much faster than the a and
b ones.} Rb5 38. Rc7+ Ke6 39. Rxg7 Rxb2+ 40. Ke3 a4 41. Ra7 b5 42. Ra6+ Ke7 43.
f4 Rb3+ 44. Kd4 a3 45. Ke5 b4 46. f5 $18) ({Another technical win starts with} 
37. b4 a4 38. b5 Rxb5 39. Rxa4 $18 {Exchanging one pair of pawns is essential
for keeping Black's counterplay under control and after placing the white rook
behind the b-pawn, winning is just a matter of time.}) 37... Ke8 38. e4 ({
Again, taking on g7 brings home the bacon. During the game, I didn't know how
to asses it, which shows lack of endgame knowledge. I felt it must be the
right way but why 'risk' it?! Now I know for sure:)} 38. Rxg7) 38... Rd4 39. f3
{Rush slowly sounds like a great piece of advice but here it is just too slow.}
(39. Ke3 Rb4 40. Rxg7 $18 {With an even better version than before.}) 39... b5
40. Ke3 Rb4 41. Rc2 ({Once again, White is winning after} 41. Rxg7 {even with
sloppy play.} Rxb2 42. Ra7 Ra2 43. e5 b4 44. Rb7 Rb2 45. f4 a4 46. f5 $18)
41... g5 {It doesn't look winning anymore, Black sets up the resistance.} 42.
Rd2 Rb3+ {Just a vengeful check which only helps White to finally bring the
king over.} ({Black can obtain a draw with} 42... a4 43. Kd3 Ke7 44. Kc2 Rc4+ {
and if White tries to enter via a2:} 45. Kb1 b4 46. Ka2 b3+ 47. Ka3 Rc2 $11)
43. Kd4 Ke7 44. Kc5 {Such generosity....White returns the favour.} ({Instead,
going after Black's pawns is a much better plan.} 44. Ke5 a4 45. Kf5 $18) 44...
a4 45. Kd5 {Trying to correct the error.} Rb4 {And Black allowed it.} ({
The path for a draw is set by rolling those pawns again.} 45... b4 46. Ke5 (46.
Kc4 h5 $11) 46... a3 47. bxa3 bxa3 48. Ra2 Rb5+ 49. Kd4 Rb3 50. Kc4 Rb2 51.
Rxa3 Rxg2 52. h4 gxh4 53. Kd4 (53. Kd3) (53. f4 Rg4) 53... h3 54. f4 h2 55. Rh3
Kf6 56. Rxh6+ Kg7 {However, with a human eye I would say that the final
position should be winning for White due to the connected free pawns on the e
and f files but the tablebase says draw!}) 46. Rc2 Kd7 {It is hard now to make
more mistakes.} 47. e5 Rb3 48. e6+ Ke7 49. Rc7+ Kd8 50. e7+ Ke8 51. Ke6 1-0

